Religious distribution indicates that Hinduism was the most prevalent religion, accounting for 84.9% of the population, while Buddhism represented 8.2%, Islam 4.3%, Christianity 1.2%, and Kirat 1.4% ![The table appears to show a distribution of a population or sample across different age groups for September 2014](image8).&#x20;

&#x20;

Geographically, the population is divided into Mountain, Hill, and Tarai regions, with the Tarai region holding the largest share at 50.2%, followed by the Hill region at 43.1%, and the Mountain region at 6.7% ![The table shows the percentage distribution of a population between rural and urban areas](image10]. The distribution across development regions shows Central region having the highest population share (36.5%), followed by Eastern (21.9%), Western (18.7%), Mid-Western (13.3%), and Far-Western (9.6%) ![The table displays the percentage of the population adhering to different religions over two time points](image9]. The rural population constitutes 83% while the urban population accounts for 17% [1, 9, image12].

In September 2014, Nepal's population showed distinct distributions across caste/ethnicity, religion, and geographic location, with Hinduism and the Tarai region having the highest representation.

